1.
All variables have a type, name and value
int x = 5; int = type, x = name, 5= value
string dummy = "test"; string = type, dummy = name, "test = value

2.
True: all variables must be declared before being used

3.
You can reassign a variable but you cannot declare

int x = 5;
x = 7; is reassigning

int x = 5;
int x = 7; is not valid

4.
answer = valid variable name
1stValue = variable name cannot starting with an integer [0-9]
value1 = valid variable name
$message = not valid due to the $
delete-me = hyphen is not valid
delete_me = valid variable name
PI = valid variable name
